\subtree{\title{Discussion}

\p{353: Dummett thinks verificationism is one-sided: focusing only on the \em{introduction} rules (circumstances of application) and not the \em{elimination} rules (consequences of application).
}
\p{355: Consider Sellars' focus on "first person observation reports" and Rorty's "Incorrigibility as the mark of the mental".
}
\p{358: [Judgment as interiorization of assertion](q-0062)
}
\p{359: Whether to treat something as conscious or not is \em{our prerogative}, not the world's.}

\p{360: Let's be pragmatic about who we want to grant the social status of "sentient" to.
}
\p{363: E.g. A cry of pain is a tool to get someone to \em{do} something.
}
\p{364: Our best interpretation of their behavior is that that they actually calculated. This isn't "evidence they calculated" this is \em{what it means to mentally calculate}. This is a \em{sense dependence} on social peers, not a \em{reference dependence}.
}
\p{371: And we have authority over our grammar. Though our causal interaction with the world means the world factors into how we want to / ought to change our grammar.
}
\p{375: Speaking to oneself isn't really an action we can take insofar as it is something that we can be \em{fail} at. this is why I endorse: [Judgment as interiorization of assertion](q-0062)
}
\p{381: By mastering the language, one has the status of being able to make first person observation reports under standard conditions. The only explanation one can give for saying "this is red" is explaining why one is in standard conditions (e.g. the lighting is normal, I haven't been blinded, etc.)
}
\p{383: [Depsychologizing](q-0030) quote very relevant. Psychology studies the phenomenon of thought. W. is studying the concept of thinking (i.e. the grammar of 'thinking'), which is a \em{normative} matter.
