\p{498: Example of metaphor / changing the language game: "Bring me sugar" and "Bring me milk" are commands in the present game, but "Milk me sugar" has only effect of making someone stare blankly (it is not a \em{command} to make someone stare blankly even if you intend that effect).
}
\p{499-500: Saying "This combination of words makes no sense" is itself a move that has lots of meanings in different contexts. Something being "senseless" is not the essence (sense) of that combination of words. One is not \em{describing} the sentence, one is \em{doing} something (excluding it from the language, withdrawing from circulation).
}
\p{550: Negation is itself a move that has lots of meanings in different contexts. We cannot worry about correct inferences for a word (because changing the inferences changes the meaning, so it might as well be a different word). E.g. whether #{\neg \neg P \implies P}
}
\p{554: Double negation would not be possible if it were expressed by raising pitch of one's voice.
}


